			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Freon: An Open Web Native Language Workbench</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JosWarmer.html">Jos Warmer</a>, <a href="../profile/AnnekeKleppe.html">Anneke Kleppe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567515">10.1145/3567512.3567515</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Freon is a language workbench that generates tooling for a given language definition.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It targets DSL definition and the generation of DSL-specific editors/tools.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> A major goal is improving the end-user editing experience through integrated tooling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
